Scottish private schools maintain a record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another collection of outstanding exam results, which is only reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community subjects.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), strive to offer the best level to pupils and their parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for higher education, for the career they choose and their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we are seeing that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable topic within schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, that gets to his head.
But if you speak to him in his own language, he will come to his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to establish relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's recent exams, we can see that the languages are at the top of the board and with the highest approval rates in private schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained an outstanding degree.
The data, compiled from the 74 schools that make up the SCIS, shows that 72% of pupils received an honorary enrollment in Mandarin, while 72% of students who studied German, 69% of students who studied French and 63% of students who studied Spanish also achieved an outstanding.
This shows that Scottish private schools support languages and consider them key skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, languages are taking the same consideration as subjects such as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in private school programs and of all kinds.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Training Commission in 2014 indicated that among the lack of knowledge of languages constitutes 17% of the reasons for employers to cover vacancies.
Therefore, linguistic skills are becoming increasingly necessary to prepare young people for their future careers.
These skills are essential in a globalized world, as there are more job opportunities that need languages.
Regardless of your chosen career, learning a second language will have a real advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will place a bilingual person directly at the head of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% did not speak any foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, in this case 15%.
This is why it is so important to invest in language for children today.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, provides children with more opportunities to find a meaningful job.
In Scotland, the teaching languages differ according to the school.
Some schools focus on the most classic modern languages, while others are taught by languages considered most important to the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interests of their children, private schools always have several languages to choose from and specialist teachers in this field.
Scottish private schools specialize in providing a learning environment that prepares children and teams with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future holds for them.
We cannot deny that at this time, in a global business environment, languages remain vital for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communicative skills".
Private schools will continue to offer this diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do it right.
