This year, a new Harvard University course is making all of its students sleep more in order to combat the growth of the male culture of studying all night caffeine-stimulated.
One academic found that students at the world's number one university often don't know the basic aspects of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard School of Medicine and a specialist at Brigham and Muller Hospital, conceived the course, which is believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the impact sleep deprivation had on learning.
“At the end of the course, a girl approached me and said, ‘Why are you telling me this only now, in my last year?’
He said no one had told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was launched this year for the first time, explains to students the basic aspects of how acquiring good sleep habits helps with academic and athletic performance, as well as improves overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard School of Medicine and the university’s executive director of health services, said the university decided to present the course after discovering that students had a significant lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course involves a series of interactive tasks.
In a section there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light and how sleep deficiency affects athletic performance, as well as the importance of having a routine at bedtime.
In another section, participants are informed how prolonged lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that it will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know this information, just as we have a right to know what the health effects are if we opt for tobacco smoking,” Professor Czeisler added.
