Red tide information: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to the latest report by the Florida Wildlife and Fisheries Conservation Commission, there is a general reduction in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the committee, increasingly unequal deforestation conditions are being observed in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and the counties of Collier, which may mean that concentrations are being reduced.
The red tide extends approximately 210 km from the coast from the northern counties of Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
Concentrations can be found 16 km away from the county of Hillsborough, but in fewer places compared to last week.
There was also a red tide in the county of Pasco.
The presence of mid-level concentrations on the coast or far from the coast of Pinellas County was reported last week, bottom and high concentrations far from the coast of Hillsborough County, bottom and high concentrations far from the coast of Sarasota County, bottom and high concentrations far from the coast of Sarasota County, bottom and low concentrations far from the county, with low and high level concentrations of Char County, and low level in the county County County.
In the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier it is reported that cases of respiratory irritation continue to occur.
No case of this type was reported in northwestern Florida last week.
